WEBVTT 

1
00:01:06.858 --> 00:01:09.452
<i>I got my nickname from this song.</i>

2
00:01:09.528 --> 00:01:13.908
When I was in the Army they used to
mispronounce Segerman as Sugar Man.

3
00:01:13.991 --> 00:01:17.211
And then they just started calling me
Sugar and that became my nickname.

4
00:01:18.245 --> 00:01:23.797
<i>It's 40 years since this LP called
Cold Fact by Rodriguez was released.</i>

5
00:01:24.418 --> 00:01:27.467
<i>And in South Africa
it was a very popular album.</i>

6
00:01:27.546 --> 00:01:30.345
<i>It was one of the biggest albums
of the day.</i>

7
00:01:30.424 --> 00:01:33.519
<i>But the thing was.
we didn't know who this guy was.</i>

8
00:01:33.594 --> 00:01:36.689
<i>All our other rock stars.
we had all the information we needed.</i>

9
00:01:36.763 --> 00:01:39.186
<i>But this guy? There was nothing.</i>

10
00:01:39.266 --> 00:01:42.611
<i>And then we found out
that he had committed suicide.</i>

11
00:01:42.686 --> 00:01:47.533
<i>He set himself alight on stage and
burnt to death in front of the audience.</i>

12
00:01:48.233 --> 00:01:51.362
<i>It was the most incredible thing.
It wasn't just a suicide.</i>

13
00:01:51.445 --> 00:01:55.245
<i>It was probably the most
grotesque suicide in rock history.</i>

14
00:04:07.622 --> 00:04:12.253
The first time that I remember
actually recognizing him is

15
00:04:12.335 --> 00:04:14.838
Mike Theodore called me
on the phone one day and said.

16
00:04:14.921 --> 00:04:17.800
"I have this artist
I want you to come see with me.

17
00:04:17.883 --> 00:04:19.681
"This guy's name is Rodriguez.

18
00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:21.728
"he's working down by the Detroit River.

19
00:04:21.803 --> 00:04:23.646
"There's a bar down there.

20
00:04:23.722 --> 00:04:26.271
"down by the wharf riverside district.

21
00:04:26.349 --> 00:04:27.726
"Let's go see him tonight.

22
00:04:27.809 --> 00:04:29.061
"I think you'll really like him."

23
00:04:29.644 --> 00:04:33.445
<i>So that night. I remember.
we pull up...</i>

24
00:04:33.565 --> 00:04:36.694
<i>away in this kinda isolated
part of Detroit</i>

25
00:04:36.777 --> 00:04:38.825
<i>right on the side of the Detroit River.</i>

26
00:04:38.904 --> 00:04:42.750
<i>and you could see the mist in the air
coming off the river. We could feel it.</i>

27
00:04:42.824 --> 00:04:46.545
And we went inside there.
and as we walked in the door.

28
00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:49.339
we could hear behind us
the sound of the freighters

29
00:04:49.414 --> 00:04:51.132
as they're going down the river.

30
00:04:51.208 --> 00:04:54.553
and so it's like you're walking out
of a Sherlock Holmes novel.

31
00:04:54.628 --> 00:04:58.007
You walk out of the mist
and you go into this place.

32
00:04:58.089 --> 00:05:00.558
and inside the place.
it's all full of smoke.

33
00:05:00.634 --> 00:05:02.261
so there's a mist inside there.

34
00:05:02.677 --> 00:05:05.897
<i>Boom. hey. you know.
it's a wall of smoke.</i>

35
00:05:06.848 --> 00:05:10.569
<i>Beer all over the place. Peanut shells.
It was just a mess.</i>

36
00:05:10.644 --> 00:05:14.649
And then you hear this strumming sound.

37
00:05:15.232 --> 00:05:16.700
Strumming and batting the guitar.

38
00:05:19.736 --> 00:05:24.242
And then you hear this voice.
Strange voice.

39
00:05:24.324 --> 00:05:26.702
<i>Finally. we walked
through the smoke. and I looked.</i>

40
00:05:26.785 --> 00:05:29.254
<i>and there in the far corner I saw...</i>

41
00:05:29.329 --> 00:05:32.674
I could see the shadow of a man
and I couldn't see his face.

42
00:05:32.749 --> 00:05:35.719
I said. "What's the deal?"
So we got a little closer...

43
00:05:37.379 --> 00:05:41.680
<i>And you see this guy
with his back to you.</i>

44
00:05:42.342 --> 00:05:46.722
<i>So all you see is his back
and he's in a corner. singing.</i>

45
00:05:47.347 --> 00:05:50.942
<i>It was an ethereal scene. if you will.</i>

46
00:05:51.017 --> 00:05:56.444
Foggy night. foghorns. smoke so thick
you couldn't see through it.

47
00:05:57.190 --> 00:05:59.067
<i>And here's this voice.</i>

48
00:05:59.609 --> 00:06:01.611
<i>Maybe it forced you
to listen to the lyrics</i>

49
00:06:01.695 --> 00:06:03.697
<i>'cause you couldn't see the guy's face.</i>

50
00:06:03.780 --> 00:06:07.080
<i>That's when we talked to him and figured
we needed to do an album on him.</i>

51
00:06:07.158 --> 00:06:11.459
The only writer that I had heard of.
of that time period.

52
00:06:11.538 --> 00:06:15.042
was maybe Bob Dylan.
that was writing that well.

53
00:07:35.038 --> 00:07:38.383
<i>He was this wandering spirit
around the city.</i>

54
00:07:38.458 --> 00:07:42.088
<i>And. uh. sometimes
I might catch him in the corner.</i>

55
00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:45.640
You know. Detroit's got its share of.
uh. burned-out. desolate areas

56
00:07:45.757 --> 00:07:48.931
and I would occasionally see him. um.

57
00:07:50.178 --> 00:07:51.976
far away from The Brewery.
and I wondered.

58
00:07:52.055 --> 00:07:55.309
and it just added
to this mythology of him.

59
00:07:55.392 --> 00:07:59.113
Like. what is he doing?
What is he doing? What does he do?

60
00:07:59.187 --> 00:08:03.784
I heard he did a little roofing.
some construction work.

61
00:08:03.858 --> 00:08:06.953
Um. I think that's how he got his money
at the time.

62
00:08:07.028 --> 00:08:09.656
He just was. you know.
and I say this with love.

63
00:08:09.781 --> 00:08:12.125
I say this with respect. but.

64
00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:14.202
I thought he was just a...

65
00:08:14.869 --> 00:08:19.090
just not much more than a kind of
a homeless person. you know?

66
00:08:19.165 --> 00:08:22.214
He just was a drifter.
He was just... Um...

67
00:08:23.294 --> 00:08:26.118
<i>I didn't know if he had a home.
you know?</i>

68
00:08:26.314 --> 00:08:29.964
<i>He'd look like maybe he'd go
from shelter to shelter or something.</i>

69
00:08:35.932 --> 00:08:38.105
<i>Detroit in the '70s was a hard place.</i>

70
00:08:38.184 --> 00:08:39.777
<i>Well. it's still a hard place.</i>

71
00:08:39.853 --> 00:08:44.984
<i>Lot of decay. lots of ruined houses.
Real poverty exists in this city.</i>

72
00:08:45.066 --> 00:08:48.445
<i>And those streets
were Rodriguez's natural habitat.</i>

73
00:08:48.528 --> 00:08:51.657
Any time we met him
to talk about what we were doing.

74
00:08:51.781 --> 00:08:55.661
he would always meet us on a corner
somewhere in his neighbourhood.

75
00:08:55.785 --> 00:08:58.254
Most of the time
he wasn't coming to my house.

76
00:08:58.329 --> 00:09:01.378
He'd say. "Meet me on the corner
of this street and that street."

77
00:09:01.458 --> 00:09:02.960
and we would be there.

78
00:09:03.043 --> 00:09:06.172
Uh. Mike and I would get out of our cars
and park our cars.

79
00:09:06.254 --> 00:09:07.631
so we'd be standing on the corner.

80
00:09:07.714 --> 00:09:09.387
and then we'd look round
and he'd be there all of a sudden.

81
00:09:09.466 --> 00:09:10.934
He'd just show up.

82
00:09:11.009 --> 00:09:13.853
<i>We thought he was like
the inner city poet.</i>

83
00:09:13.928 --> 00:09:17.523
<i>You know? Putting his poems to music
of what he saw.</i>

84
00:09:18.141 --> 00:09:20.815
<i>And it was definitely a very gritty look</i>

85
00:09:20.894 --> 00:09:23.067
<i>at what he saw
on the streets of Detroit.</i>

86
00:09:23.146 --> 00:09:26.650
<i>What he saw in his neighbourhood.
Who was walking around the streets.</i>

87
00:09:26.816 --> 00:09:31.822
<i>And the way he presented it in a song.
I thought was very. very interesting.</i>

88
00:09:32.572 --> 00:09:35.967
<i>We were working
at Tera-Shirma recording studio.</i>

89
00:09:36.159 --> 00:09:40.085
<i>When he opened up and sang.
you went. "Whoa. this guy's got it."</i>

90
00:09:40.663 --> 00:09:46.011
<i>Rodriguez. at that time.
had all the machinery in place.</i>

91
00:09:47.170 --> 00:09:50.925
<i>Big names. big money behind it.
Circumstances were right.</i>

92
00:09:51.007 --> 00:09:55.683
<i>Why didn't it make it? That's the
big question that today still haunts me.</i>

93
00:09:55.762 --> 00:09:59.437
Did he get enough promotion?
Did he do enough performances?

94
00:10:00.266 --> 00:10:02.018
Was he too political?

95
00:10:03.853 --> 00:10:05.596
Was there this or was there that?

96
00:10:05.688 --> 00:10:07.941
Should it have been green
instead of orange?

97
00:10:08.024 --> 00:10:11.119
Should it have been a violin
instead of an oboe?

98
00:10:11.194 --> 00:10:12.992
On and on you can go.

99
00:10:13.780 --> 00:10:17.626
But the end of the day is. if you
listen to the stuff now. you'd say.

100
00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:20.670
"I don't understand it. he's right-on."

101
00:10:23.331 --> 00:10:24.958
<i>I only heard him play once.</i>

102
00:10:25.041 --> 00:10:29.512
<i>and one of the songs that
he had on his album. it was called...</i>

103
00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:34.384
<i>The Sugar Man? Was it Sugar Man?
Is that the name of the song?</i>

104
00:10:34.509 --> 00:10:37.288
Um. I knew that guy. the Sugar Man.

105
00:10:37.387 --> 00:10:40.732
And his name was Volkswagen Cha...
Volkswagen Frank!

106
00:10:40.807 --> 00:10:42.229
And he lived right around the corner

107
00:10:42.350 --> 00:10:44.478
and you used to go over
to Volkswagen Frank's.

108
00:10:44.561 --> 00:10:47.735
<i>You'd go in and get a little "sugar."
if you know what I mean.</i>

109
00:11:35.737 --> 00:11:38.786
I got some photos here
that I'd like to show you

110
00:11:38.948 --> 00:11:44.626
that I've kept since my days in England
with Rodriguez.

111
00:11:44.746 --> 00:11:46.219
Let me see.

112
00:11:46.414 --> 00:11:49.793
Possibly it's in this book.
I don't know where.

113
00:11:51.044 --> 00:11:54.218
These are all my photos
from when I was acting.

114
00:11:54.297 --> 00:11:58.373
That's me. and that's Jimmy Dean.
That was in 1955.

115
00:11:58.468 --> 00:12:02.814
Hang on. I think I've found them.
Think they're in here.

116
00:12:04.557 --> 00:12:06.309
Yeah. here they are.

117
00:12:07.435 --> 00:12:10.279
Wow. Good Lord. here they are.

118
00:12:10.813 --> 00:12:15.319
You know. I haven't seen these pictures
in almost 35 years.

119
00:12:18.279 --> 00:12:20.498
He's my most memorable artist.

120
00:12:21.324 --> 00:12:24.168
You know. I've produced
a lot of great ones. but...

121
00:12:26.663 --> 00:12:28.665
he's my most memorable.

122
00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:31.167
<i>It's not just a talent.</i>

123
00:12:32.502 --> 00:12:33.924
<i>He's like...</i>

124
00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:37.369
<i>He's like a wise man. a prophet.</i>

125
00:12:37.465 --> 00:12:41.186
<i>He's way beyond
just being a musical artist.</i>

126
00:12:41.844 --> 00:12:44.347
<i>And he probably could have done
fantastically well</i>

127
00:12:44.472 --> 00:12:45.849
<i>if he had have continued.</i>

128
00:12:45.932 --> 00:12:49.937
When I met him. they said.
"Rodriguez. this is Steve Rowland.

129
00:12:50.019 --> 00:12:52.863
"He really likes your album."
And Rodriguez said to me.

130
00:12:52.939 --> 00:12:55.893
<i>"Well. did you like Cold Facts?"</i>

131
00:12:56.192 --> 00:12:58.766
I said. "Man. I thought
it was absolutely brilliant.

132
00:12:58.861 --> 00:13:00.363
"Absolutely brilliant.

133
00:13:00.446 --> 00:13:04.201
"I can't believe that this album
didn't do anything.

134
00:13:04.325 --> 00:13:06.874
"It's just a fantastic album."

135
00:13:07.036 --> 00:13:08.438
So he played me...

136
00:13:08.538 --> 00:13:12.714
Well. his next album was on...
In those days you had cassettes.

137
00:13:12.834 --> 00:13:17.305
He had demos of this next album that
he was gonna call Coming From Reality.

138
00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:22.557
And I said. "Wow. man.
this has got to be a smash.

139
00:13:22.677 --> 00:13:24.224
"These are great songs.

140
00:13:24.345 --> 00:13:29.897
"Little bit... Little bit different from
the others." I said. "but great songs."

141
00:13:30.393 --> 00:13:33.237
I said. "And a couple of them
were so sad." You know.

142
00:13:33.313 --> 00:13:36.567
There's one in there
that's absolutely a killer.

143
00:13:36.691 --> 00:13:38.639
It's one of the saddest songs that...

144
00:13:38.735 --> 00:13:43.832
I'm laughing. but it's one of
the saddest songs that I've ever heard.

145
00:13:43.906 --> 00:13:47.151
And it's a very simple song.
Hang on. I wanna play this. Hang on.

146
00:13:47.243 --> 00:13:49.541
Okay. listen to these words.

147
00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:12.727
Oh. man.

148
00:14:54.602 --> 00:14:57.506
<i>And it really makes me sad. because...</i>

149
00:14:57.605 --> 00:15:00.404
<i>that was the last song that we recorded.</i>

150
00:15:00.983 --> 00:15:04.533
<i>And that was the last song
that Rodriguez ever recorded.</i>

151
00:15:06.614 --> 00:15:10.209
And what makes it even sadder

152
00:15:10.326 --> 00:15:13.671
was the album was released
in November of 1971.

153
00:15:14.956 --> 00:15:18.961
and we expected big things.
And it did absolutely nothing.

154
00:15:21.337 --> 00:15:24.341
And then. two weeks before Christmas.

155
00:15:25.842 --> 00:15:28.311
Sussex dropped him off the label.

156
00:15:28.845 --> 00:15:33.421
And the very first line in the song.
as if premonition.

157
00:15:33.516 --> 00:15:37.396
was. "I lost my job
two weeks before Christmas."

158
00:15:40.022 --> 00:15:42.491
Oh. man. I just think about that.

159
00:15:43.651 --> 00:15:47.656
This guy deserves recognition.

160
00:15:48.030 --> 00:15:52.035
Nobody in America had even heard of him.

161
00:15:53.536 --> 00:15:54.879
Nobody...

162
00:15:57.248 --> 00:16:00.343
Nobody even was interested
in listening to him.

163
00:16:03.254 --> 00:16:07.384
How can that be? How can that be?
Guy that writes like this.

164
00:16:08.718 --> 00:16:10.220
I mean...

165
